(
<figureCitation id="13412A65FF9DE536D4FFFDA6D7EB46E1" box="[671,737,631,653]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="4.[144,223,1853,1872]" captionTargetBox="[368,1198,1236,1823]" captionTargetId="figure-333@4.[367,1199,1235,1824]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 5. Geographical distribution of Leptolebias in Rio de Janeiro state, south-eastern Brazil: 1, L. marmoratus, L. splendens, and L. opalescens; 2, L. marmoratus and L. opalescens; 3, L. splendens; 4, L. citrinipinnis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4634949" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4634949/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="156">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC536E0FF9DE536D6C4FD17D7EF40E4" blockId="9.[164,779,710,1160]" pageId="9" pageNumber="156">
<emphasis id="B90EEAF2FF9DE536D6C4FD17D7DE46B7" box="[164,724,710,731]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="156">
Habitat and conservation: 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D63FF9DE536D7BBFD17D7DE46B7" baseAuthorityName="Myers" baseAuthorityYear="1942" box="[475,724,710,731]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Leptolebias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="156" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendens">Leptolebias splendens</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
was a common fish in the Estrela river basin until 1944 (A. L. Carvalho and H. S. Lopez, pers. comm.), when the region still contained well-preserved forests near and along the old road Rio–Petrópolis. After this time, both the forest and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D63FF9DE536D7EEFC8ED7164718" baseAuthorityName="Myers" baseAuthorityYear="1942" box="[398,540,863,884]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Leptolebias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="156" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis id="B90EEAF2FF9DE536D7EEFC8ED7164718" box="[398,540,863,884]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="156">L. splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
disappeared. It was rediscovered 41 years later in temporary pools within a well-preserved forest belonging to a group of Brazilian scouts (Costa &amp; Lacerda, 1988), in the Roncador river basin. However, although the forest is still well preserved today, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D63FF9DE536D7FCFC29D7234061" baseAuthorityName="Myers" baseAuthorityYear="1942" box="[412,553,1016,1037]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Leptolebias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="156" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis id="B90EEAF2FF9DE536D7FCFC29D7234061" box="[412,553,1016,1037]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="156">L. splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has not been found since 1987. Part of the stream draining the forest was diverted to a neighbouring fish farm, which apparently altered the water levels of aquatic bodies in the forest. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7A4D63FF9DE536D695FBA3D4E540EB" baseAuthorityName="Myers" baseAuthorityYear="1942" box="[245,495,1138,1159]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Leptolebias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="156" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis id="B90EEAF2FF9DE536D695FBA3D4E540EB" box="[245,495,1138,1159]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="156">Leptolebias splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may now be extinct.
</paragraph>
